The formula for the remaining amount of a radioactive substance is: \[ N(t) = N_0 \times \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{t}{t_{1/2}}} \] Given that the activity is 6% of the original amount, we have: \[ 0.06 \times N_0 = N_0 \times \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{t}{12.5}} \] Dividing both sides by \( N_0 \): \[ 0.06 = \left( \frac{1}{2} \right)^{\frac{t}{12.5}} \] Taking the natural logarithm of both sides: \[ \ln(0.06) = \frac{t}{12.5} \times \ln\left( \frac{1}{2} \right) \] Simplifying using \( \ln\left( \frac{1}{2} \right) = -\ln(2) \): \[ \ln(0.06) = \frac{t}{12.5} \times (-\ln(2)) \] Solving for \( t \): \[ t = \frac{12.5 \times \ln(0.06)}{-\ln(2)} \] Calculating the values: - \( \ln(0.06) \approx -2.8134 \) - \( \ln(2) \approx 0.6931 \) Substituting these values: \[ t = \frac{12.5 \times (-2.8134)}{-0.6931} \approx \frac{35.1675}{0.6931} \approx 50.74 \] Rounding to the nearest whole number and considering significant figures, the age of the whiskey is approximately 51 years. \[ \boxed{51} \]
